[normal]Scottish Ministers own the National Forest Estate on behalf of the Scottish people, and contract Forest Enterprise Scotland
[normal] (FES)
[normal], which is designat
[normal]ed as a public corporation for national accounting purposes, to manage it.
[normal] 
[normal]http://www.forestry.gov.uk/pdf/ScotlandAccounts2012-13.pdf/$FILE/ScotlandAccounts2012-13.pdf
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]This is accounted for under the 
[normal]“Sustainable Forest Management” (SFM)
[normal] budget heading
[normal] which covers forest planning, timber operations, forest protection and maintenance (including deer management), management and development of the estate, and sufficient social and environmental activity to ensure continued UKWAS compliance.
[normal] 
[normal]The apparent o
[normal]perating deficit 
[normal]in 2012-13 
[normal]for net sustainable forest management was £36.3M, although this includes £31.3M for the value of felled timber: subtracting this reduces the deficit to £5.1M. 
[normal]which
[normal] was apparently mainly due to the cost impact on impairments to 
[normal]the value of buildings (in 2011-2 
[normal]the 
[normal]SFM budget had a £2.9M surplus).
[normal] The
[normal]se “additional benefits” are subdivided into
[normal] “Communities, recreation and tourism” (net cost £13.0M), “Environment and heritage” (net cost £7.3M) and “Estate improvements” (net cos
[normal]t £12.4M) – in respect of which FCS received government grant of £32.7M
[normal]. The published accounts do not break down expenditure under these budget headings, but they incorporate significant staff and organisational costs, as well as cash expenditure.
[normal] Natio
[normal]nal Forest Estate covers c. 660kha. Valuations of ground rents to date range from £20-30/ha pa, which gives a range of £13.2-19.8M. Note, however that these valuations have been for properties designated surplus by FCS and are therefore likely to be below 
[normal]the mean value of the estate.
[normal] Net timber income as reported in FES accounts was £34M, if deductions for restock (4,700ha in 2012-3) are estimated at £2-3k/ha, then timber payments in years 1-5 would be 80% of £19.9-24.6M, i.e. £15.92-19.68M
